{:proof/problem-id "apm-a98J04", :proof/classification :partial, :proof/output "\n\n---\n\nTARGET SANITY CHECK — mentions-problem-objects? ✅ (complex-differentiable \\(f:\\mathbf C\\to\\mathbf C\\), real Jacobian, the specific maps \\(g,h\\)) · avoids-assuming-conclusion? ✅ (the main claim concludes the CR-form matrix and excludes \\(g,h\\); it isn’t assumed) · meaningful-without-prose? ✅ (even standalone it’s a concrete matrix-structure theorem) · notes: helper lemma captures the Cauchy–Riemann-to-matrix translation that directly refutes the two examples.\n\n```clojure\nPROOF-PLAN.EDN\n{:goal \"Explain why the real Jacobian of a complex-differentiable map must be of the Cauchy-Riemann form, and why the matrices for g(x,y)=(x,-y) and h(x,y)=(x,2y) violate this.\"\n :terms [{:name \"real and imaginary parts\"\n          :meaning \"Write f = u + i v with u,v : Real^2 -> Real and express the Jacobian via their partial derivatives.\"\n          :needed-because \"Complex differentiability can be translated into conditions on the real Jacobian.\"}\n         {:name \"Cauchy-Riemann equations\"\n          :meaning \"u_x = v_y and u_y = -v_x for complex differentiable maps.\"\n          :needed-because \"They force the Jacobian to have the special form [[a,-b],[b,a]].\"}\n         {:name \"Jacobian matrices of g and h\"\n          :meaning \"Compute Dg = diag(1,-1) and Dh = diag(1,2).\"\n          :needed-because \"These matrices clearly fail the CR symmetry, so g,h cannot arise from a complex differentiable function.\"}]\n :strategy [{:id :s1\n             :formal-dependency \"Complex.differentiable_iff_CauchyRiemann\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Stage 1 rewriting f=u+iv\"\n             :why-this-now \"Translate complex differentiability into CR equations for u and v.\"\n             :lean-target \"jacobian_has_CR_form\"\n             :mathlib-status \"Mathlib already provides Cauchy-Riemann expressed via real derivatives.\"}\n            {:id :s2\n             :formal-dependency \"matrix_form_from_CR\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Output of :s1\"\n             :why-this-now \"Show the Jacobian equals [[u_x,-u_y],[u_y,u_x]] with u_x=v_y, etc.\"\n             :lean-target \"cr_matrix_block\"\n             :mathlib-status \"Follows algebraically once CR equations hold.\"}\n            {:id :s3\n             :formal-dependency \"matrix_comparison\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Structure from :s2\"\n             :why-this-now \"Compute Dg,Dh and note they do not equal [[a,-b],[b,a]].\"\n             :lean-target \"g_h_fail_CR\"\n             :mathlib-status \"Direct matrix arithmetic.\"}]\n :stage-status {:stage1 :done :stage2 :done :stage3 :in-progress :stage4 :pending}}\n```\n\n```clojure\nFORMAL-ALIGNMENT.EDN\n{:main-claim {:informal-claim \"Every complex-differentiable f:Complex->Complex has real Jacobian [[a,-b],[b,a]] at each point, so the matrices of g(x,y)=(x,-y) and h(x,y)=(x,2y) cannot occur.\"\n             :formal-name \"jacobian_CR_form\"\n             :formal-target \"forall f : Complex -> Complex, Differentiable Complex f →\n  forall z, ∃ a b : ℝ,\n    jacobianReal f z = Matrix (2×2) !![[a, -b], [b, a]] ∧\n    Matrix (2×2) !![[1, 0], [0, -1]] ≠ jacobianReal f z ∧\n    Matrix (2×2) !![[1, 0], [0, 2]] ≠ jacobianReal f z.\"\n             :sanity-check {:mentions-problem-objects? true\n                            :avoids-assuming-conclusion? true\n                            :meaningful-without-prose? true\n                            :notes \"States the CR symmetry and rules out the two examples.\"}}\n :alignments [{:formal-name \"jacobian_CR_form\"\n              :formal-statement \"same as formal-target\"\n              :informal-clause \"Main statement.\"\n              :role :main-theorem}\n             {:formal-name \"cauchy_riemann_matrix\"\n              :formal-statement \"jacobianReal f z has the block form [[a,-b],[b,a]] whenever f is complex differentiable.\"\n              :informal-clause \"Provides the symmetry used to exclude g and h.\"\n              :role :helper-lemma}]}\n```\n\n---\n\n**Why it’s hard.**  Complex differentiability is defined by a limit in ℂ, yet the question forces you to translate everything into real coordinates. It’s easy to forget that “complex-linear” means the Jacobian must commute with a 90° rotation matrix, so many students either treat this as a routine Jacobian computation or overlook the Cauchy–Riemann constraints entirely—making it unclear why *every* holomorphic map has a very special 2×2 derivative.\n\n**Key insight.**  Split \\(f(x+iy)=u(x,y)+iv(x,y)\\). Complex differentiability is equivalent to the Cauchy–Riemann equations \\(u_x=v_y\\) and \\(u_y=-v_x\\). Those two equalities force the real Jacobian\n\\[\nJ_f=\\begin{pmatrix}u_x & u_y\\\\ v_x & v_y\\end{pmatrix}\n\\]\nto equal \\(\\begin{pmatrix}a & -b\\\\ b & a\\end{pmatrix}\\), i.e. multiplication by \\(a+ib\\) in disguise. The matrices for \\(g(x,y)=(x,-y)\\) and \\(h(x,y)=(x,2y)\\) are \\(\\mathrm{diag}(1,-1)\\) and \\(\\mathrm{diag}(1,2)\\), which plainly do **not** have this form.\n\n**Complete proof.**  \nLet \\(f=u+iv\\) be complex differentiable at \\(z_0=x_0+iy_0\\). The functions \\(u\\) and \\(v\\) are real differentiable and satisfy the Cauchy–Riemann equations \\(u_x(x_0,y_0)=v_y(x_0,y_0)\\) and \\(u_y(x_0,y_0)=-v_x(x_0,y_0)\\). Thus the Jacobian matrix of \\(f:\\mathbb R^2\\to\\mathbb R^2\\) at \\((x_0,y_0)\\) equals\n\\[\nJ_f(x_0,y_0)=\\begin{pmatrix}u_x & u_y\\\\ v_x & v_y\\end{pmatrix}_{(x_0,y_0)}\n=\\begin{pmatrix} a & -b\\\\ b & a\\end{pmatrix},\n\\]\nwhere \\(a=u_x=v_y\\) and \\(b=v_x=-u_y\\) at that point. Therefore the derivative is multiplication by the complex number \\(a+ib\\); in real coordinates the matrix must be of the above symmetric form.\n\nNow \\(g(x,y)=(x,-y)\\) has constant Jacobian\n\\[\nDg=\\begin{pmatrix}1&0\\\\0&-1\\end{pmatrix},\n\\]\nwhich would force \\(a=1\\), \\(b=0\\) from the first row and simultaneously \\(a=-1\\), \\(b=0\\) from the second row—impossible. Similarly \\(h(x,y)=(x,2y)\\) has\n\\[\nDh=\\begin{pmatrix}1&0\\\\0&2\\end{pmatrix},\n\\]\nwhich would require \\(a=1=b\\) and \\(a=2\\) at once, again impossible. Hence neither \\(g\\) nor \\(h\\) satisfies the Cauchy–Riemann symmetry enjoyed by derivatives of complex-differentiable functions.\n\n**Lean 4 formalization.**  \n- Artifacts updated: `proof-plan.edn`, `formal-alignment.edn`, `execute.md`, and `changelog.edn` under `/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a98J04/apm-v2-a98J04-1775004924027/`.\n- Strategy: use Mathlib’s fact that `fderiv ℂ f z` is ℂ-linear; translate ℂ-linearity into the 2×2 Cauchy–Riemann matrix; show the linear maps associated with \\(g\\) and \\(h\\) do not commute with multiplication by \\(i\\).\n- Status: steps (1)–(2) require a lemma turning “ℂ-linear” into the explicit matrix \\(\\begin{pmatrix}a & -b\\\\ b & a\\end{pmatrix}\\). Mathlib currently lacks that bridge, so `Main.lean` only contains the planned skeleton. Once a lemma of the form  \n  `lemma complexLinear_matrix (L : ℂ →ₗ[ℂ] ℂ) : ∃ a b, matrixReal L = [[a,-b],[b,a]]`  \n  is implemented or imported, wiring it into the proof and running `lake build` should finish the formalization.\n\n**What connects.**  This is the “real form” of the Cauchy–Riemann equations. The same check—real Jacobian of the form \\(\\begin{pmatrix}a & -b\\\\ b & a\\end{pmatrix}\\)—shows up whenever you test a real-linear map for complex linearity: in proving the maximum modulus principle, showing harmonic conjugates exist, or verifying whether a linear PDE preserves holomorphic functions. Keep the CR-matrix criterion handy; it’s the quickest algebraic test for complex differentiability.", :proof/extraction {:phases {}, :dependency-graph nil, :arse-questions nil, :classification :partial, :phase-count 0, :dep-graph-count 0, :arse-count 0}, :proof/frame-workspace {:frame/lean-root "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/A98J04/Apm_v2_a98J04_1775004924027", :frame/id "apm-v2-a98J04-1775004924027", :workspace/owner-repo "futon6", :workspace/generated-at "2026-04-01T00:55:24.053584Z", :frame/shared-extension-root "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Local", :frame/module-root "ApmCanaries.Frames.A98J04.Apm_v2_a98J04_1775004924027", :proof/problem-id "a98J04", :workspace/schema "proof-frame-workspace.v1", :frame/workspace-root "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a98J04/apm-v2-a98J04-1775004924027", :artifacts {:proof-plan "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a98J04/apm-v2-a98J04-1775004924027/proof-plan.edn", :formal-alignment "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a98J04/apm-v2-a98J04-1775004924027/formal-alignment.edn", :changelog "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a98J04/apm-v2-a98J04-1775004924027/changelog.edn", :execute-notes "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a98J04/apm-v2-a98J04-1775004924027/execute.md", :workspace-readme "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a98J04/apm-v2-a98J04-1775004924027/README.md", :workspace-metadata "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a98J04/apm-v2-a98J04-1775004924027/workspace.json", :lean-main "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/A98J04/Apm_v2_a98J04_1775004924027/Main.lean", :lean-scratch "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/A98J04/Apm_v2_a98J04_1775004924027/Scratch.lean"}}, :proof/artifacts ["/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/A98J04/Apm_v2_a98J04_1775004924027/Main.lean" "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/A98J04/Apm_v2_a98J04_1775004924027/Scratch.lean"], :proof/elapsed-ms 113142}